    "answer": "Most common isolated congenital heart defect Left to right shunt, pulmonary over-perfusion, pansystolic murmur is typical. Chest X-rays often show cardiomegaly and increased pulmonary vascularity, check history of URTIs, very large air embolism risk (clear all iv lines from bubbles - paradoxical emboly), Urinary output is a key surrogate for cardiac output (target >1 cc/kg/hr), review echos esp. PAP and calculated resistance, palliative care with a band around PA, heart failure in large VSD with digitalis and diuretics (withheld digitalis preop), premed  oral midazolam (0.5 mg/kg) or IM ketamine (3–5 mg/kg) for anxious children with difficult venous access, pulmonary hypertension, Eisenmenger syndrome (reversal of shunt with cyanosis), small VSDs can close spontaneously, large VSDs cause heart failure and require closure (surgical or cath), if PAH develops > no closure possible, avoid increases in PVR (hypoxia, hypercapnia, acidosis) and decreases in SVR (vasodilation) to prevent shunt reversal, fixed PA hypertension is most dangerous (hypoxia, co2, hypothermia, acidosis, atelectasis, hyperinflation, pain/stress > sympathetic stimulation and pulmonary hypertension), induction and maintenance with very large fentanyl doses up to 100 mcg/kg, Cardiopulmonary Bypass (CPB): Requires heparin (3–4 mg/kg) to achieve an Activated Coagulation Time (ACT) >480 seconds (ideally >600s, Weaning from CPB: Facilitated by volume and inotropic support (commonly Dopamine or Dobutamine) and vasodilators to control PVR/SVR, Extubation: Early extubation in the ICU is appropriate for uncomplicated cases. However, patients with pulmonary hypertension should remain intubated for 2–3 days while following a pulmonary hypertension drug protocol, heart block is common and should be treated with pacing, Phenylephrine (pure alpha-1 agonist). It increases SVR without increasing heart rate or contractility,",
    "section": "anae_doc"
