    "question": "What are perioperative considerations for a patient with Fallot tetralogy?",
    "answer": "Most common cyanotic congenital heart defect, KEEP PVR low and SVR HIGH (RLS low then), Four anatomical abnormalities: Ventricular Septal Defect (VSD), Pulmonary Stenosis (PS), Overriding Aorta (moved to the right side and originates at the VSD), Right Ventricular Hypertrophy (RVH) - often in DiGeorge syndrome, undergo complete repair between 6–18 months of age Some may have had palliative B-T (Blalock-Taussig) shunts (if pulmonary stenosis is too severe - A. subclavia to pulmonary artery), to maintain pulmonary perfusion, Uncorrected: Problem RLS > low SaO2 (pain, stress, hypovolemia), anesthesia: keep PVR low and SVR high > this will lower RLS, increase preload, keep PVR low (high FiO2, pCO2 low, avoid acidaemia), SVR and MAD with Noradrenaline to keep RR high and reduce RLS > VSD- Patch, RVOT- plasty, Most common cyanotic congenital heart defect, four anatomical abnormalities: Ventricular Septal Defect (VSD), Pulmonary Stenosis (PS), Overriding Aorta, Right Ventricular Hypertrophy (RVH). Cyanosis, dyspnea, fatigue, and syncope, especially during exertion. Surgical repair is typically performed in infancy or early childhood, Avoid increases in pulmonary vascular resistance (PVR) (e.g., hypoxia, hypercapnia, acidosis) and decreases in systemic vascular resistance (SVR) (e.g., vasodilation) to prevent worsening of the right-to-left shunt. Use of beta-blockers to reduce infundibular spasm and maintain a slow heart rate can be beneficial. Low peep and V pressures to keep PVR low and prevent RLS deterioration, polycythaemia (Hct >0.65 may require venesection), maintain Systemic Vascular Resistance (SVR) and minimize Pulmonary Vascular Resistance (PVR) to reduce right-to-left shunting, Premedication: Essential to avoid crying/stress which increases PVR and can trigger a \"tet\" spell (during feeding or crying); A tetralogy or ‘tet’ spell (also known as a cyanotic spell, or hypercyanotic spell), Historically, ketamine was favored to preserve SVR, but careful titration of any induction agent is acceptable, Knee-to-chest position (increases SVR and reduces deoxygenated venous return), 100% Oxygen (acts as a pulmonary vasodilator), Fluid boluses and sedation/analgesia (e.g., IV morphine/fentanyl) to reduce sympathetic drive, Phenylephrine to increase SVR, Beta-blockers (esmolol/propranolol) to relieve infundibular spasm, Obstetrics: High risk for uncorrected TOF, Use sequential low-dose combined spinal-epidural (CSE) or epidural techniques to avoid sudden SVR drops, Be cautious with uterotonics: Syntocinon causes hypotension, and Carboprost (PGF2alpha) increases PVR, Complications: Be vigilant for air embolism (use air filters on IV lines due to the VSD) and infective endocarditis prophylaxis in high-risk cases",
