    "question": "What are perioperative considerations for a patient with Fontan pathology",
    "answer": "Staged approach to reduce hypoxia (venous and returning pulmonary blood mix (via ASD or/and VSD) and reduce strain on the ventricle, PUT SYSTEMIC and PULMONARY CIRCULATION IN SERIES despite a single ventricle, Single ventricle heart (8% of inborn errors) > Single functional ventricle undergo a staged surgical process that converts their systemic and pulmonary circulations from parallel to in-series, Passive Pulmonary Flow: Unlike a normal heart, there is no sub-pulmonary ventricle to pump blood to the lungs; instead, systemic venous blood flows passively into the pulmonary arteries, Transpulmonary Pressure Gradient: The driving force for pulmonary blood flow is the difference between central venous pressure (CVP) and atrial pressure, Key Complications: Patients are prone to ventricular dysfunction (systolic and diastolic), atrial arrhythmias (poorly tolerated and may require immediate cardioversion), thromboembolism, and protein-losing enteropathy, Perioperative Anesthetic Management > The primary goal is to maintain the transpulmonary pressure gradient by ensuring adequate preload and minimizing pulmonary vascular resistance (PVR) 1. Preoperative Optimization > Conduct a detailed history and physical exam, focusing on functional status and signs of end-organ damage from chronic high venous pressure Obtain a 12-lead ECG and echocardiography to assess rhythm, valvular function, and ventricular contractility, Administer antibiotic prophylaxis for any procedure likely to cause bacteraemia, 2. Hemodynamic Goals > Maintain Preload: These patients are highly preload-dependent; even moderate hypovolemia is tolerated poorly and will drop cardiac output, Minimize PVR: Strenuously avoid factors that increase PVR, such as hypoxia, hypercarbia, acidosis, and inadequate analgesia, Maintain Sinus Rhythm: This is vital for optimal ventricular filling and atrial emptying, Avoid Vasoconstrictors: α-adrenergic agonists should be avoided as they increase PVR; similarly, β-blockers should be used with caution due to negative inotropic effects, 3. Induction and Maintenance > Agents: Avoid myocardial depressants like thiopental Propofol is generally safe if the patient is normovolemic Maintenance: Use low concentrations of volatile agents (<1.5 MAC) to avoid arrhythmias, ideally combined with an opioid infusion (e.g., remifentanil) for stability, Monitoring: Invasive arterial and CVP monitoring are mandatory for major surgery to guide fluid administration, Transoesophageal echocardiography (TOE) or esophageal Doppler can help assess preload and cardiac output, 4. Ventilation Strategy > Spontaneous Breathing: Preferred for short procedures to avoid the negative effects of positive pressure on venous return, Mechanical Ventilation: If necessary, use low respiratory rates, short inspiratory times, and low PEEP, Tidal Volumes: Keep volumes at 5–6 ml/kg to prevent high mean intrathoracic pressures that decrease pulmonary blood flow, 5. Special Considerations > Pregnancy: Epidural anaesthesia is the technique of choice for delivery, as it avoids the PVR-increasing effects of general anesthesia, though it must be titrated carefully to avoid sudden hypotension, Laparoscopy: Most patients tolerate this if intra-abdominal pressure is kept ≤10 mm Hg; higher pressures compress the IVC and severely reduce cardiac output, Embolic Risk: Patients with a fenestration (a residual right-to-left shunt) are at high risk for paradoxical air or fat emboli. The older Fontan patient is at particular risk of thromboembolism, arrhythmias and progressive ventricular dysfunction. Heart function in the pregnant patient with a Fontan circulation deteriorates throughout pregnancy. Elective delivery under epidural anaesthesia is usually the technique of choice. Laparoscopic and day care surgery is usually well tolerated in the young Fontan patient.",
