    "question": "What are perioperative considerations for a patient with the TGA pathology",
    "answer": "Aorta arises from the right ventricle (RV) and the pulmonary artery from the left ventricle (LV), Systemic and pulmonary circulations exist in parallel rather than in series. Deoxygenated blood recirculates to the body, and oxygenated blood recirculates to the lungs, Survival is impossible without communications (PFO/ASD, VSD, or PDA), Atrial-level mixing is the most effective, Left Ventricle (LV) Deconditioning: In TGA with an intact ventricular septum, the LV mass rapidly involutes after birth as pulmonary vascular resistance (PVR) drops. If surgery is delayed beyond 2–4 weeks, the LV may fail to support systemic pressures after repair, Perioperative Management Preoperative Stabilization: Prostaglandin E1 (PGE1): Infused to maintain PDA patency for mixing, Balloon Atrial Septostomy (BAS): Performed if mixing is inadequate or if the ASD is restrictive; it improves saturations by tearing the atrial septum, Surgical Options: Arterial Switch Operation (ASO): The standard anatomical repair involving vessel translocation and coronary artery transfer, Arterial Switch Operation (ASO): This is the gold standard, occurring in approximately 80% of cases. It involves cutting the aorta and pulmonary artery just above where they leave the heart and switching them to their proper ventricles (aorta to left ventricle, pulmonary artery to right ventricle). Coronary Artery Transfer: During the ASO, the coronary arteries must be detached from the original aorta and moved to the new aorta (\"neo-aorta\"). Lecompte Maneuver: Often used during the ASO, this maneuver brings the pulmonary arteries forward to sit in front of the aorta to prevent future narrowing. Balloon Atrial Septostomy (BAS): A catheter-based procedure (often done before surgery) to improve mixing of oxygenated and deoxygenated blood.",
